04082nam a2200565Ia 9781438448459DE-B159720240602123719.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||240602t20132013nyu    fo  d z      eng d  a9781438448459  a(DE-B1597)684298  a(OCoLC)1428236203  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anyucUS-NY 7aPHI0220002bisacsh04a181/.06qOCoLC223/eng/202302161 aTepper, Aryeh, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aProgressive Minds, Conservative Politics :bLeo Strauss's Later Writings on Maimonides /cAryeh Tepper. 1aAlbany : bSUNY Press, c[2013] 4c©2013  a1 online resource (256 p.) :bTotal Illustrations: 0  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aSUNY series in the Thought and Legacy of Leo Strauss00tFront Matter -- tContents -- tAcknowledgments -- tIntroduction -- tThe Guide of the Perplexed as a Jewish Book -- tThe Guide of the Perplexed as a Work of Classical Political Philosophy -- tTorah and Philosophy in The Book of Knowledge -- tConclusion -- tAppendix I -- tNew Worlds of Power -- tNotes -- tBibliography -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aLeo Strauss (1899–1973), one of the preeminent political philosophers of the twentieth century, was an astute interpreter of Maimonides's medieval masterpiece, The Guide of the Perplexed. In Progressive Minds, Conservative Politics, Aryeh Tepper overturns the conventional view of Strauss's interpretation and of Strauss's own mature thought. According to the scholarly consensus, Strauss traced the well-known contradictions in the Guide to the fundamental tension in Maimonides's mind between reason and revelation, going so far as to suggest that while the Jewish philosopher's overt position was religiously pious (i.e., on the side of "Jerusalem"), secretly he was on the side of reason, or "Athens." In Tepper's analysis, Strauss's judgments emerge as much more complex than this and also more open to revision. In his later writings, Tepper shows, Strauss pointed to contradictions in Maimonides's thought not only between but also within both "Jerusalem" and "Athens." Moreover, Strauss identified, and identified himself with, an esoteric Maimonidean teaching on progress: progress within the Bible, beyond the Bible, and even beyond the rabbinic sages. Politically a conservative thinker, Strauss, like Maimonides, located man's deepest satisfaction in progressing in the discernment of the truth. In the fullness of his career, Strauss thus pointed to a third way beyond the modern alternatives of conservatism and progressivism.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 02. Jun 2024) 0aJewish philosophy. 0aJudaism. 0aMaimonides, Moses, -- 1135-1204. -- Dalalat al-?a?irin. 0aPhilosophy, Medieval. 4aHistory : Medieval Studies. 4aJewish Studies : Jewish Philosophy. 4aJewish Studies : Jewish Studies. 4aPolitics and Law : Political Philosophy. 4aPolitics and Law : Political Theory. 7aPHILOSOPHY / Religious.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertSUNY Press eBook Package  Backlist 2000-2013z978311148737340uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781438448459423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781438448459/original  a978-3-11-148737-3  SUNY Press eBook Package  Backlist 2000-2013c2000d2013  aGBV-deGruyter-alles